                                    <h2 class="header-text--h2">Galactosemia Screening methods for newborns</h2>
                                </div>
                                <p class="paragraph-text--bold-16">Classic Galactosemia and clinical variant</p>
                                <p class="paragraph-text--medium-condensed-16">Galactosemia <strong>should be suspected</strong> in individuals with the following newborn screening results, clinical features, family history, and supportive laboratory findings<sup>1</sup>:</p>

                                <p class="paragraph-text--bold-16 text-color--secondary-blue">Newborn screening utilizes a small amount of blood obtained from a heel prick to quantify<sup>1</sup></p>

                                <ul class="ul-list--general-style">
                                    <li><span class="paragraph-text--regular-16"> Total content of erythrocyte galactose-1-phosphate and blood galactose concentration<sup>1</sup></span></li>
                                    <li><span class="paragraph-text--regular-16">Erythrocyte GALT enzyme activity<sup>1</sup></span></li>
                                    <li><span class="paragraph-text--regular-16">Biallelic pathogenic variants in GALT<sup>1</sup></span></li>
                                </ul>
                                <p class="paragraph-text--regular-16">State Newborn Screening (NBS) programs vary as to which of these tests is performedâ€“or, if both are performed, in what sequence.<sup>1</sup>
                                </p>
                            </div>
