                            <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-6 col-md-6 col-sm-12 col-xs-12">
                                <div class="pt-5 pb-4">
                                    <p class="paragraph-text--bold-20">Neurological defects persist and/or worsen throughout adulthood</p>
                                    <p class="paragraph-text--regular-16">Studies in adolescents and young adults with Galactosemia have shown <strong>both white and grey matter abnormalities consistent with the cognitive impairment</strong>, language problems, and motor disturbances
                                        observed beginning in early childhood.<sup>4,5</sup></p>

                                    <p class="paragraph-text--regular-16">Galactitol production also contributes to ovarian dysfunction. Most girls (>80%) with Classic Galactosemia develop primary ovarian insufficiency. Although the exact mechanism of <strong>ovarian dysfunction</strong>                                            has not been identified, both direct deposition of galactitol and oxidative stress induced by galactitol production are believed to contribute to this problem.<sup>8,9</sup></p>

                                    <p class="pt-4 paragraph-text--bold-20">Neurological deficits may diminish adult quality of life<sup>8,10</sup></p>
                                    <div>
                                        <p class="paragraph-text--regular-16">In adults, CNS deficits contribute to:</p>
                                        <ul class="ul-list--general-style">
                                            <li><span class="paragraph-text--regular-16">Lower academic attainment</span></li>
                                            <li><span class="paragraph-text--regular-16">Less skilled employment, more unemployment</span></li>
                                            <li><span class="paragraph-text--regular-16">An inability to form social bonds, including marriage</span></li>
                                            <li><span class="paragraph-text--regular-16">An inability to maintain independence<br> (living with parents)</span></li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </div>
                                </div>


