                                <h2 class="header-text--h2">Long-term complications and patient surveillance</h2>
                            </div>

                            <div style="padding-left: 11rem; padding-right:12rem;">
                                <p class="paragraph-text--regular-16 text-center">Patients with Galactosemia exhibit extreme heterogeneity in the complications that manifest over time. Clinical findings in early disease do not predict long-term outcomes. Moreover, there is little or no correlation
                                    between the time when dietary restriction is initiated and developmental delays, and associations of specific complications with genotype remain unclear. Therefore, <strong>ongoing vigilant surveillance of patient health
                                        status is essential.<sup>1,3</sup></strong></p>
                            </div>

                            <div class="pt-4">
                                <div class="text-center">
                                    <p class="paragraph-text--bold-24">In adolescents with Galactosemia</p>
                                    <div class="py-2" style="padding-left: 19rem; padding-right:19rem;">
                                        <p class="paragraph-text--regular-16">Approximately one-half of patients with Classic Galactosemia will experience developmental delays that emerge in infancy or early childhood and then progress.</p>
                                    </div>
